<a name="books"><H1>Debian Books</H1></a>

<p><a href="http://www.linuxpress.com/">Linux Press</a> produces a
<a href="http://www.linuxpress.com/001001.htm">Debian manual</a>.
It should be available at major bookstores (Borders carries it). The book
is also available, over the net, in html format from the website.

<p>The latest version of the book includes Debian 2.0 although there are probably
a number of copies that include 1.3 on bookshelves.
Linux Press also offers technical support to those who buy the book.
<hr>

<A HREF="mailto:J.A.Bezemer@ITS.TUDelft.NL">J.A. Bezemer</A> wrote a Dutch
Debian manual, that covers basic knowledge, installation and usage. It's
available <A HREF="http://panic.et.tudelft.nl/debian/handleiding/">online</A>
in various formats; within The Netherlands, <A
HREF="http://panic.et.tudelft.nl/debian/cd/">hardcopies</A> are also
available. 

<hr>
<A HREF="mailto:Budde@tu-harburg.de">Marco Budde</A> wrote 
<A HREF="http://www.mitp.de/online/0498/0498.html">Linux HOWTOs: Die besten
L&ouml;sung der Linuxgemeinde</A> which is a book containing two Official
Debian 2.1 CDs (main and contrib), the Debian installation guide in
German and the best German HOWTOs.

<HR>
<p>[Note: If you would like your Debian book mentioned here, send mail to
&lt;<a href="mailto:webmaster@debian.org">webmaster@debian.org</a>&gt;]


